		<description><![CDATA[I recently learned this inversely from my local bass teacher when I asked about soloing. If your static chord (or song structure) is minor (say Cminor blues) your bass solo can take off from a Major scale that begins from the minor 3rd of the static chord ( or D# in the C minor case). Both Relative minor scenarios that I had learned in theory class years ago and forgotten. To cool to hear though when you begin to play riffs!]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I recently learned this inversely from my local bass teacher when I asked about soloing. If your static chord (or song structure) is minor (say Cminor blues) your bass solo can take off from a Major scale that begins from the minor 3rd of the static chord ( or D# in the C minor case). Both Relative minor scenarios that I had learned in theory class years ago and forgotten. To cool to hear though when you begin to play riffs!</p>
